        contentEn: [
            "Among all legends associated with the Zaporizhian Sich, the story of the letter to the Ottoman Sultan is perhaps the most famous. Many people associate it directly with Ivan Sirko, although over time the legend grew into a broader symbol of Cossack freedom.",
            "According to tradition, the Ottoman Sultan once sent a message demanding that the Zaporozhian Cossacks submit to his authority. In the letter he listed his many titles, praised the power of his empire, and called upon the Cossacks to surrender peacefully.",
            "When the message reached the Sich, the Cossacks gathered in council. After hearing the Sultan's demands, they reportedly burst into laughter. To free warriors of the steppe, the very idea of submission seemed absurd.",
            "The legend says that this was when the idea of writing a reply was born. Every Cossack contributed words and suggestions. Some joked, some recalled victories in battle, and others tried to invent the sharpest possible phrases.",
            "In many versions of the tale, Ivan Sirko appears as one of the central figures. He listens to the proposals of the Cossacks, smiles at their humor, and embodies the spirit of equality and freedom that characterized the Sich.",
            "Gradually, the response became a symbol of the Cossack character itself. It contained no fear of a powerful enemy. Instead, every line expressed confidence, independence, and a determination to defend freedom.",
            "Over the years the story became so popular that it developed many variations. Different regions added their own details, and storytellers embellished the tale with colorful images and memorable scenes.",
            "The legend gained even greater fame after the creation of Ilya Repin's celebrated painting 'Reply of the Zaporozhian Cossacks to the Sultan.' The painting presented an unforgettable image of cheerful, witty, and unbreakable Cossacks.",
            "Historians continue to debate how accurately the story reflects real events. For popular memory, however, historical precision is not the most important aspect. What matters is the image of people unafraid to speak openly even to the most powerful rulers.",
            "In this legend, Ivan Sirko appears not only as a military leader but also as a symbol of personal freedom. He represents dignity, independence of thought, and the belief that liberty is worth more than promises or threats.",
            "That is why the legend of the letter to the Sultan has survived for centuries. It reminds us of humanity's desire for freedom and of the power of humor, which can sometimes be as effective a weapon as a sword or musket.",
        ],

