        contentEn: [
            "In popular imagination, Ivan Sirko was a man of the steppe. He was described not only as a Kish Otaman, but as a warrior who understood distance, silence, tracks, wind, and danger better than anyone else. That is why folk tales often connected his image with the wolf.",
            "In Cossack legends, the wolf was not merely a wild animal. It symbolized freedom, sharp instinct, independence, and the ability to survive in the harshest conditions. Popular memory saw Sirko in the same way — strong, cautious, elusive, and dangerous to his enemies.",
            "According to one tale, during a night campaign Sirko's Cossack detachment found itself in the steppe without reliable landmarks. The night was dark, the wind covered the tracks, and an enemy ambush could be waiting ahead. The Cossacks hesitated, uncertain where to go.",
            "Then, as old storytellers claimed, a gray wolf appeared before the detachment. It did not attack or flee, but seemed to call the Cossacks after it. Sirko ordered his men not to shoot the animal and to follow it. Some were surprised, but no one dared disobey the otaman.",
            "The wolf walked ahead for a long time, disappearing into the darkness and then appearing again at a distance. At last it led the Cossacks to safety, guiding them around a trap prepared by the enemy on the main road. At dawn, the wolf vanished as suddenly as it had appeared.",
            "Afterward, the Cossacks began to say that Sirko understood wolves or even shared a secret bond with them. Some versions of the legend became even more fantastic, claiming that the otaman himself could turn into a wolf in order to scout enemy camps unseen.",
            "Such stories should not be read literally. They show how strongly popular memory connected Sirko with the image of the steppe warrior. To the Cossacks, he was a man who did not lose his way in danger, who could find a path and sense the enemy before the enemy appeared.",
            "In this legend, the wolf is not a monster or merely a fairy-tale creature. It becomes a sign of natural strength. Through it, people explained Sirko's military intuition, endurance, and ability to act where others lost confidence.",
            "That is why the legend of the wolf fit so naturally into the image of Sirko as a kharakternyk. It emphasized his bond with the steppe, his inner freedom, and the special awareness of the world that could save an entire army.",
            "Today this legend can be understood as a poetic image. It reminds us that for the people, Sirko was not only a historical otaman, but part of a larger Cossack myth about freedom, danger, strength, and resilience.",
        ],

